hoodMarket: Vancouver is located across the river from Portland and ideally positioned along transportation corridors, providing easy access to highways for the area’s industrial users. The airport is a short drive south, and restaurants and retailers scattered across region provide ample amenities for residents and tenants alike.,Clark County has put itself on the map in recent years, especially in the city of Vancouver. Many residents have moved to the area, attracted by Washington’s lack of state income tax and the ability to buy goods in Oregon without paying sales tax. An increase in housing costs in Portland has also driven people north of the Columbia River. Vancouver is home to several notable employers, including Banfield Pet Hospital, PeaceHealth and Frito-Lay, which has helped increase buying power in the county and solidified a well-educated local population. ,The range of inventory here provides industrial users a number of options to fit their warehousing, distribution or manufacturing needs. Nearby industrial hubs have some of the highest rents in the greater Portland area, but many tenants are able to find affordable space that fits their needs in this part of Vancouver. Leasing activity has been robust due to the discount, resulting in a low availability rate for industrial space.

propOverview:
The property totals 5,000 SF on 1.055 acres. The 5,000 SF building is comprised of approximately 1,525 SF office and 3,475 SF of warehouse space. There are 4 offices, a reception area, and an extra large conference room that could double as a training room. The shop space is 100% heated and cooled, a rare item in Midland! There are (3) 14' OHD's and the shop is crane ready for a 5-ton crane. There is also a concrete pad behind the building with a sump that can be used for washing equipment or vehicles. The property is fenced and gated and has paved asphalt parking in front. Outside city limits, no restrictions. Sublease term through January, 2021 but available for a direct 3 or 5 year lease.
The property is located on Industrial Ave between Loop 250 and FM 1788. Industrial is adjacent to Highway 80, giving this property excellent visibility and exposure from a major thoroughfare along with convenient access to I-20, 1788, Loop 250, and the airport. This strategic location would also be convenient for employees coming from both Midland or Odessa.

propOverview: CLEAN, CLEAN, CLEAN! Great location just north of Loop 410 at I35 interchange with easy access to Wurzbach Parkway. This all masonry building is ready to move in. With a three-minute drive to 35E/SRL Thornton Freeway and I-20/Lyndon B Johnson Freeway, the drivers can reach destinations such as the Amazon Fulfillment Center in 11 minutes or the Dallas central business district in 16-minutes.  In addition, Fort Worth can be accessed within 35 minutes and the Dallas Love Field and Dallas/Fort Worth Airports are each under 45 minutes from the property.  Businesses have the ability to customize the 660,312 total square feet as needed and have access to 1,839 square feet of office space that is already built-out. Tenants will benefit from the cross-dock functionality, ESFR sprinklers, and 36’ clear heights.  This building is ideal for distribution use with 52’ x 50’ column spacing, a 60’ staging bay, 134 dock doors, 178 trailer slips, and a 185’ truck court.

hoodMarket: This area of Houston is home to suburbs such as Pearland and is ideally located for a variety of space uses. Since 2000, the population of Pearland, Texas, a suburb of Houston located about 15 miles south of Downtown Houston, has essentially quadrupled to more than 114,000 residents. Moreover, the city consistently ranks among the safest in the Lone Star State. ,From a warehouse and distribution perspective, it has direct access to State Highway 288, Texas State Highway 35, and Sam Houston Tollway that can connect distributors with the growing population in this part of Houston. As suburban south Houston continues to grow, so should industrial demand for e-commerce and distribution uses in the future. ,A notable amount of wholesale trade tenants serving the oil and gas industry are located here. Some of the area's largest industrial tenants include Texas Steel Conversion, Inc. (500,000 square feet), O'Reilly Auto Parts (490,000 square feet), Powell Industries, Inc. (430,000 square feet), RTI Fabrications, L.P. (310,000 square feet), and National Oilwell Varco (300,000 square feet).,Asking rents are noticeably below the metro average, offering an attractive discount to tenants.
propOverview: Located just 5 blocks south of Loop 610, 5400 Cedar Crest Way offers businesses a unique opportunity with more than 40,000 square feet of warehouse and office space that has seen updated electrical service, lighting, and building exteriors. Between 10 different structures on the property, industrial users have access to climate-controlled warehouses, portable office buildings, storage facilities, cranes, and high power options. The four major buildings on the property are Buildings A, B, C, and D. Building A is the main building, with a 20’ eave height, 2 (two) 45’ wide bays, 2 (two) 5-ton bridge cranes, and 480/277 volt electrical service with transformers and breaker panels strategically placed throughout the building. 7,000 square feet of the warehouse is climate controlled, and there are 4 (four) overhead doors. Buildings B and C are currently configured as machines shops, each featuring up to 480-volt power options,  2 (two) overhead doors, and climate-controlled industrial space. Building C also features a 5-ton bridge crane system that is 30’ wide and 58’ in length. Building D is the last property featuring 480-volt power service, and also offers 2 (two) overhead doors and 12’ eave heights. The expansive site features perimeter chain link fencing, a fully paved lot, and the current configuration of the buildings offers an adequate turn radius for 18-wheelers. This prime location sits just minutes from Loop 610, 2.15 miles west of the Gulf Freeway/IH45, and 5 miles southeast of the Houston Central Business District for easy transportation. Additionally, the William P Hobby Airport is accessible in a 15-minute drive and the Port of Houston can be reached in 11 minutes. This central location also offers easy access to food, shopping, and daily conveniences options for employees. The building is surrounded by dense residential areas, providing a robust labor pool that will enjoy the short commutes to and from work.

hoodMarket: The Northeast Dallas area is a well-established, in-town industrial center in the metroplex. The area is diverse and can be segmented by areas inside LBJ Freeway and outside LBJ Freeway. The largest concentration of industrial tenants fall outside of LBJ Freeway towards Garland. An outer ring suburb, Garland is one of Dallas-Fort Worth’s original boomburbs, with heavy concentrations of industrial employment and blue-collar employment base. ,Geography and transportation are strategic considerations for tenants in this part of Dallas. The area includes primary transportation arteries: the LBJ Freeway, U.S. 75 North, and in the outer section, President George Bush Tollway. The existing tenant base includes manufacturing firms, retail and wholesalers, and transportation. The largest tenants include Kraft Foods, which has a large manufacturing location in Garland; home goods store At Home, which has a large distribution facility; and watch retailer Fossil, which has space near its corporate headquarters in Richardson.,With one of the largest existing inventories of industrial buildings, new construction in Northeast Dallas has been limited compared to other rapidly growing areas of Dallas-Fort Worth. Largely built-out, available land is the biggest constraint for new buildings.,Given excellent highway and rail access, robust leasing activity is keeping vacancies low. Rental rates are on par with the Dallas-Fort Worth average.
propOverview: Right on the outskirts of Dallas, 1501 Kings Road in Garland, Texas, presents a large built-out industrial facility with excess land big enough for future expansion. The 154,968 square-foot warehouse is configured to accommodate both a single business or multiple businesses, with an 85,968 square-foot warehouse, a 66,548 square-foot warehouse, and a 1,878 square-foot office/maintenance shop. The larger warehouse section features 31’ clear height, 14 8’x10’ dock-high doors with levelers and seals included, and one dock-high door with a metal ramp. The smaller warehouse section offers 15’ clear heights with the option to expand to 31’, ten 8’x10’ dock-high doors with levelers and seals included, and the office/maintenance shop space. The entire facility is 100% sprinklered and air-conditioned and features 480-volt, 3-phase, 4-wire power at 3,000 amps, 24’x36’ column spacing, a secured truck court, and ample car and trailer parking. The option also exists to secure the entire site fully. The additional 5.77 acres on the parcel could be used for building expansion, but also lends well to parking, trailer storage, or outside storage. 1501 Kings Road is positioned just five minutes from I-635/Lyndon B Johnson Freeway, which conveniently connects to the surrounding major highways. There is also an active rail line located seven minutes away, the Dallas Love Field Airport is 29 minutes away, and the Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport is just 37 minutes away. Businesses enjoy access to a sizable employee base as the building is 10 minutes from downtown Garland and only 22 minutes from downtown Dallas.

hoodMarket: Centrally located in Dallas-Fort Worth, Upper Great Southwest is one of the largest concentrations of industrial space in the area. Directly north of Arlington and equidistant between Dallas and Tarrant counties, Upper Great Southwest is a longstanding industrial district that serves North Texas. The area is served by excellent access to highways and is adjacent to D-FW International Airport. With 14 of the top 20 major cargo hubs served, the airport provides the domestic and international lift to meet the increased demands of e-commerce and just in time logistics. ,National retailers, 3PLs, and firms focused on distribution are active tenants in the area. For instance, Office Depot, Discount Tire and home appliance company Haier all have a presence in the area. The inventory here is a mix of smaller, vintage buildings from the 1960s to modern buildings with expansive footprints. Newer buildings include taller clear heights and accommodate multi-modal transportation. ,Construction activity in Upper Great Southwest has been significant.  Developers have grown existing inventory about 25% in the past decade. Many properties have been build-to-suit, though the area is a popular among developers adding spec space as well. Robust demand for industrial space has kept vacancy rates stable. Rents for flex space trend at a premium relative to both general industrial space in the area as well as Dallas-Fort Worth.
propOverview: 805 W Carrier Parkway is in an ideal location for businesses to thrive within the Dallas/Fort Worth metroplex. Building signage has frontage on W Carrier Parkway, at the signalized intersection of W Carrier Parkway and 109th Street, where it is visible to 17,905 cars that pass by each day. The building features front parking, rear loading design, and there are two fenced truck court entries, one on W Carrier Parkway and the other on 109th Street. The spaces at 805 W Carrier Parkway are move-in ready and recently remodeled. They are ideal for research and development, light manufacturing, logistics, or any other similar use, and the available suite has ample warehouse space with 18’ clear height and two dock-high doors. The building is under new ownership, who completed updates that include LED lighting in the offices, updated lighting in the warehouse space, new countertop finishes, and a fresh coat of paint. They have also implemented best-in-class property management to handle any issues so tenants can focus on their business. 805 W Carrier Parkway benefits from its proximity to many major roadways and highways throughout the region. I-20, I-30, TX-161, TX-183, and TX-360 are all easily accessible, and the building is equidistant to both Dallas and Fort Worth, reaching downtown in either city in under 30 minutes. Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport is even closer, reachable in a 10-minute drive. Grand Prairie is in what is considered the Mid-City region of the Dallas/Fort Worth metroplex, and has excellent demographics, with around 979,808 residents in a 10-mile radius, expected to grow by almost 7% in the next five years.

propOverview: Situated on a 7.3-acre business park in the desirable Near Northwest submarket, 6507 West Little York Road offers amenities and conveniences to meet the needs of today’s industrial tenants. The Northwest Place Industrial Park features five attractive, tilt-wall facilities and a fully curbed and nicely landscaped access road that connects Bingle and West Little York Roads. 6507 West Little York boasts a rare drive-thru opportunity with 2 (two) 12’x12’ and 2 (two) 16’x16’ grade-level, over-sized roll-up doors. The site offers ample outside storage and employee parking options, and from the connecting road commuters, customers and cargo alike enjoy easy access to the nearby major highways. Both I-45 and I-10 are reached in 15 minutes or less, and from there, three major airports can be reached in an hour drive or less. The Houston George Bush Intercontinental Airport is 26 minutes from the site, the William P Hobby Airport is 41, and the Ellington Field Airport is 54. It is also only a 30-minute drive to the Port of Houston and an 8-minute drive to the Tencon Industries, Inc rail line. The Near Northwest industrial submarket has experienced low vacancy rates and strong demand for space over the past few years. With no reported industrial space under construction as of the end of 2019, 6507 West Little York Road offers an excellent opportunity for tenants to locate their business in this area.

hoodMarket: In the age of e-commerce and just in time logistics, moving goods to consumers has become increasingly important. Known as West D-FW Airport, the industrial zone on the western side of Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport is among the few places in North Texas that provides that value. It’s located in one of America's fastest-growing cities near interstates paired with unparalleled international and domestic connectivity from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport. ,The airport has made a concerted effort to increase its industrial offering in the past few years. As a result, the total tonnage has grown by double digits, and new cargo carriers now serve the area. In addition to the accessibility to global markets, many of the properties and developable land fall within the airport's Foreign Trade Zone. Companies operating in this area receive numerous inventory tax exemptions for international inventory. They benefit from reduced customs duties, tariffs, and taxes, potentially saving companies millions of dollars while providing direct airport ramp access and reducing shipping times.,West D-FW Airport’s vacancy rates typically track lower than the rest of Dallas-Fort Worth Because of the numerous advantages of this location, rents are usually higher than in many other industrial nodes. However, higher rents have not slowed leasing activity, which has remained strong in West D-FW Airport throughout this economic expansion.

hoodMarket: The North Hardy Toll Road’s location between the heavily trafficked Interstate 10 and Beltway 8, as well as its proximity to the George Bush Intercontinental Airport, makes it well positioned to satisfy demand generated by the nearby population growth. ,Since 2010, more than 80% of Harris County's population growth has occurred in its unincorporated areas. The majority immediately to the west and increasingly the east of the submarket, especially with the completion of the Grand Parkway. The North Hardy Toll Road also benefits from rooftop growth in Montgomery County to the north, particularly Springwoods Village, The Woodlands, and Conroe. The area draws distribution tenants looking to be close to the fastest-growing population region in Houston and in a newer stock of buildings. ,The area’s industrial inventory has grown by nearly 50% since 2010. Yet vacancies remain relatively low. Among the largest recent developments, Grocers Supply and Conn’s HomePlus moved into their build-to-suits in the area recently. And DB Schenker moved into its new distribution location nearby. Distribution tenants tend to prefer buildings with higher clear heights, stronger load bearing walls, and larger truck bays.,Rents in the North Hardy Toll area are below neighboring areas, particularly to the north and west.
propOverview: Presidents Park is Houston's newest and most flexible master-planned industrial project.  The first installment, Presidents Park 5, is currently under construction and is expected to be completed in Q2 2020.  This speculative building can suit either single or multi-tenant needs with glass storefront entrances on both ends and ample auto and trailer parking.  The state-of-the-art, front-load space will have 32' clear height, a modern 185' truck court, LED interior and exterior lights, and ESFR sprinklers.  The park itself is undergoing major infrastructure improvements including upgrading and expanding Milner Road for easier and quicker access in and out of the park. Presidents Park’s strategic location in north Houston, immediately south of IAH Airport, provides unmatched access to the ever-growing Houston MSA population and business centers. The park is located less than 5 miles from all three major north/south arteries, including I-45, Hardy Toll Road and Hwy 59, and boasts immediate access to Beltway 8 and a 10-minute drive to the 610 Loop for excellent circulation around the city of Houston. This key location combined with Presidents Park’s best-in-class design and state-of-the-art facilities creates an ideal setting for future growth.

highlights: Large air-conditioned warehouse that is drive through. Secure, discrete back yard storage. Nice offices and work rooms. 1/4 mile from Loop 820,Lots of natural light. Large, shop wide compressed air system.
propOverview:
I am offering my 4750 sq. ft. Warehouse/shop/offices for lease for $3750 per month.  Utilities and yard keep are the responsibility of the leasee. 
The building sits on 0.41 acres with a fenced and secure back yard, accessible by a 10' secure steel gate.  great location, 1/4 mile from northwest Loop 820. 
The property has been used as a high end automotive shop for the last 10 years and currently has (3) 11,000 lb car lifts. There is ample room for more or these can be removed if desired. In addition to the 3200 sq ft warehouse/shop area, there are 5 offices or work rooms, reception/area, kitchen/break area, (2) restrooms, one with shower, and a 500 sq. ft. equipment room. It would serve many types of businesses and had been a commercial HVAC company before I acquired it. 
The offices and warehouse are insulated and air-conditioned and heated. Electrical service is 400 amps, single phase with many 240v and 120v outlets. There are 14 skylights in the warehouse and 4 skylights in the equipment room that provide ample daylight inside on sunny days. There are overhead storage racks, mezzanine storage as well as numerous shelving. There is a 8'x10' door with electric opener on the front side and a manual 10'x10' door in the rear. The equipment room has a 8'x8' manual roll up door. One large sink is in the shop area and there is a large, wall mounted exhaust fan. The warehouse and equipment room are plumbed for compressed air supplied by a large Quincy air compressor in the equipment room. 
Wifi and security system. Ample parking. Availability May 1 or possibly earlier. 
Contact me for an appointment to view.

highlights: 14’4” – 18’-foot clear span ceiling heights.,Total of 4 ground-level vehicle doors.,Excellent access to freeway.,Heated and insulated warehouse area.,Total of 5 dock-high vehicle doors (via recessed dock).,Approximately 10% office to warehouse ratio.
propOverview:
THIS OFFERING is for the opportunity to lease a first-class steel frame flex warehouse.  Constructed in 2000 and historically occupied by a bakery for distribution, the building includes 5 ground-level vehicle doors and 4 dock-high vehicle doors (via recessed loading doc), is clear span with approximately 14’4” ceiling heights at the eves and approximately 18’ at the center, is heated and insulated and includes nicely appointed office space consisting of approximately 10% of the building area.  .    
Located within an established, vibrant industrial submarket area, the property has excellent freeway access to I-82 and includes reciprocal access through the adjacent industrial park.  
Existing tenant is currently occupying the building on a month-to-month basis, therefore the building is anticipated to be available within 30-60 days.
